@NODE "reqs" " "Special Requirements""





                             Special Requirements:




            SFSMui uses @{"MagicUserInterface" link mui} By Stefan Stuntz .

              The Latest MUI can be found at http://www.sasg.com/



           All you'll need if you don't already have it is the Superb

                               SmartFileSystem By

                 John Hendrikx http://www.xs4all.nl/~hjohn/SFS/

                         Currently FreeWare (30/11/99)



@ENDNODE
@NODE "feat" "Features"





                       SFSMui has all of these features..
                       ----------------------------------





          Finds SFS Partitions:  @{"     " LINK "devg"} : Knows a SmartFileSystem
 calls a RigidDiskBlock Editor:  @{"     " LINK "rdbe"} : to Add/Remove/Update Partitions


  Configurable Default NewName:  @{"     " LINK "newn"} : 'EmptySFS' By Default
    Use Device Name as NewName:  @{"     " LINK "dname"} : eg. Call Device DH1: DH1


 Has a Case Sensitivity Switch:  @{"     " LINK "case"} : Select Case Sensitivity
         Toggle .Recycle Modes:  @{"     " LINK "recy"} : SHOWRECYCLED or NORECYCLED


            Other Command Page:  @{"     " LINK "Other"} : Add/Remove/Run Any SFS Command


                   Preferences:  @{"     " LINK "prefs"} : Set the Configuration

                  Onboard Help:  @{"     " LINK "onhelp"} : Press Help For the Guide

@ENDNODE
@NODE "devg" "Device Gadget"




            The "Device" gadget selects A SmartFileSystem Partition



    SFSMui uses internal dos functions to get a list of All SFS Partitions.

              It reads the DosList structure and accepts any disk
                        who's dostype starts with 534653



@ENDNODE
@NODE "rdbe" "RidgidDiskBlock Ediitor"





                            RidgidDiskBlock Ediitor
                            -----------------------



                      A RidgidDiskBlock Editor is used to

              add/remove/change partitions/FyleSystems on your HD

               By Default this is set to run Sys:Tools/HDToolBox



           you can select any RDB Editor in the @{" Prefs " LINK prefs} Section

@ENDNODE
@NODE "newn" "Def New Name"





                                Default New Name

               Enter a Volume name for a freshly formatted device

           Defaults to 'EmptySFS' but can be set to anything you like

@ENDNODE
@NODE "dname" "Same Name as Device"





   If you click the "Same" Gadget the NewName will be the same as the device


                ie.  Device Dh1: will Set The Volume Name to Dh1

@ENDNODE
@NODE "case" "Toggle CaseSensivity"





                             Toggle CaseSensivity

                    The "CaseSense" CheckBox gadget Chooses
                     CaseSensitivity ON/OFF with SFSFormat

@ENDNODE
@NODE "recy" ".Recycled Mode"





                             Slecting .Recycle Mode

             Here you can toggle between the 3 ".Recycle dir" Modes

              SFSFormat has 2 switches to change the .Recycle mode

      but only 1 or none can be given as NORECYCLED Overrides SHOWRECYCLED

      The 3 Modes Are...

Hide .Recycled: The Default (no args).
       gives a .Recycled dir but it's Hidden . ie. it can only be seen
       by typing the path in a shell or filerequester

Show .Recycled: adds SHOWRECYCLED to the format command.
       gives a .Recycled dir and it shows as a normal WB icon

  No .Recycled: adds NORECYCLED to the format command.
       Does Not give a .Recycled dir

@ENDNODE
@NODE "prefs" "Configuration"





                              SFSMui's Settings.




   "SFS Format" is the path to SFSFormat .  eg. C:SFSFormat

   @{" RDB Editor " link rdbe} is the Path To Your SCSI Editor . eg. SYS:Tools/HDToolBox

   @{" New Name " link newn} is the default new device name, eg. Empty

   "Save: Envarc" saves the settings to both ENV: and ENVARC:

   "Save: Env" saves the settings to ENV: only
   "Load Envarc" Re-Reads ENVARC:SFSMui.cfg and restores all gadgets

   "Load Env" Re-Reads ENV:SFSMui.cfg and restores all gadgets


   ALSO. You can @{" Add Other SFS Commands " link Other}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Other" "The Other Commands Page"





                           The "Other" Commands Page

                By Default SFSMui adds 3 commands to the GUI..
             you can start SFSQuery , SFSDeFragmentGUI or SFSCheck.


USAGE:

 To use another SFS Command first

 Select a Device (if required)

 select the "Other" Page

 Then Press "Run command"


CONFIGURATION:

                      to configure Select The "Other" Tab

     Select an item, Double Click it or Press edit to call the Edit Window

  A Command has 3 configurable fields

  Name: any name you like

  Command: The path to the command and then you set the args.

  Insert fields like this.

  \%c = Command
  \%d = Device Name (without colon)
  \%n = New Name (as New Name gadget)

  Perhaps Some @{" Examples " LINK exam} would help you Understand :)

@ENDNODE
@NODE "exam" "Example Command Syntax"





                           Example Command Strings...


command = C:SFSFormat
   args = run \%c drive "\%d:" name "\%n"

runs SFSFormat in the default console on the selected drive and calls
it Empty (if Empty is set as the Default NewName)



command = C:SFSDefragGUI
   args = run >nil: \%c \%d:

runs C:SFSDefragGUI on Selected Drive WITHOUT CLI OUTPUT




command = C:SFSHoldme
   args = %c %d:

Launches C:SFSHoldme "will use Default CLI output if necessary"
this method (without "run") will disable SFSMui
until the process is over

@ENDNODE
@NODE "using" "Using SFSMui"





                                  Using SFSMui

                     To Start from WB Double Click the Icon

                         To start from CLI just run it


    There Are 3 Pages for the GUI


    @{"     " LINK func} : The Format Window

    @{"     " LINK other} : The "Other Commands" Window

    @{"     " LINK prefs} : The Prefs Window


@ENDNODE
@NODE "func" "SFSMui Format Page"





                            SFSMui's Format Page


            The text display at the top displays the selected drive

  @{"    " LINK newn} "Name" is the volume to use name when formatting a drive

  @{"    " LINK dname} "Same" sets "name" to the device name (without colon:)

  @{"    " LINK case} "Casesense" gives SFSFormat the CASESENSITIVE arg (or not)

  @{"    " LINK rdbe} "RDB" runs your partition editor

  @{"    " LINK recy} You can choose either Hide/Show or None modes for the .Recycled dir

  @{"    " LINK devg} "Device" selects the SmartFileSystem partition

        "Format" will Run SFSFormat

        "Q" Quits SFSMui


 ALSO see About the   @{" Other " LINK other} Page, used to run any other SFS Commands




@ENDNODE
@NODE "onhelp" "Onboard Help"





                                  Onboard Help
                                  ------------



              As well as MUI\'s Bubble Help appearing over Gadgets
          Pressing HELP will use Amigaguide to load the SFSMui.Guide

                    SFSMui.Guide MUST be in help:english dir


                 it will load relevent pages if you are on the
                   Format,Prefs or Other Commands windows

@ENDNODE
@NODE "mui" "MUI - MagicUserInterface"




                        MUI - MagicUserInterface

                              Version 3.8

                  (c) Copyright 1992-97, Stefan Stuntz

------------------------------------------------------------------------

MUI  is  an object oriented system to create and maintain graphical user
interfaces.  From  a programmers point of view, using MUI saves a lot of
time  and  makes life much easier. Thinking about complicated terms like
window resizing or font sensitivity is simply not neccesary.

On  the  other hand, users of MUI based applications have the ability to
customize  nearly every pixel of a programs interface according to their
personal taste.

Please click on the Install-MUI icon to install MUI on your system or to
update from previous versions.  Latest news and support  can be found on
Internet at www.sasg.com.

